# üê≥ **Docker Installation & Basic Commands ‚Äì Practice Guide**

This guide covers **Docker installation and basic commands on Linux**, including container management, image handling, and **Nginx testing**.

---

## **1. Install Docker**

```bash
curl -fsSL https://get.docker.com -o install-docker.sh
Explanation:
Downloads the official Docker installation script and saves it as install-docker.sh.

ls
Explanation:
Verifies that install-docker.sh is downloaded.

sh install-docker.sh
Explanation:
Installs Docker Engine on the system.

2. Verify Docker Installation
docker --version
Explanation:
Confirms Docker installation and shows version.

3. Container Management
docker ps
Explanation: Shows running containers only.

docker ps -a
Explanation: Shows all containers (running + stopped).

4. Image Management
docker images
Explanation:
Lists all locally available Docker images.

5. Run Test Container
docker run hello-world
Explanation:
Validates Docker installation.

6. Run Ubuntu Container (Interactive)
docker run -it ubuntu
Explanation:
Starts Ubuntu in interactive mode.

7. Start Existing Container
docker start <container_id>
Example:

docker start 8aafca4a6f92
Explanation:
Starts a stopped container.

8. Access Container Terminal
docker exec -it <container_id> /bin/bash
Example:

docker exec -it 8aafca4a6f92 /bin/bash
Explanation:
Opens terminal inside a running container.

9. Create Image from Container
docker commit <container_id> <new_image_name>
Example:

docker commit 8aafca4a6f92 anuragiswrongimage
Explanation:
Creates a new image from container state.

10. Pull Nginx Image
docker pull nginx
Explanation:
Downloads the official Nginx image.

11. Run Nginx Container
docker run nginx
Explanation:
Runs Nginx without external access.

12. Run Nginx with Port Mapping
docker run -p 80:80 nginx
Explanation:
Maps container port 80 to host 80.

13. Run Nginx in Background with Name
docker run --name docker-nginx -d -p 80:80 nginx
Explanation:

--name ‚Üí Container name

-d ‚Üí Detached mode

-p 80:80 ‚Üí Port mapping

14. Common Mistake
‚ùå Wrong

docker run --name -d docker-nginx -p 80:80 nginx
‚úÖ Correct

docker run --name docker-nginx -d -p 80:80 nginx
Reason:
--name must be followed by the container name.

15. Command History
history
Explanation:
Shows previously executed commands.

üéØ Practice Tip
After running Nginx with port mapping, open your browser:

http://localhost
If you see the Nginx Welcome Page, Docker networking is working perfectly! üöÄ

